passages.text: Expect Strong Consumer Demand, New EV Pre- Buy, & OEM Absorption of Tariff Costs to Keep US LV SAAR Elevated \(>16 \mathrm{mn}\) Against the August Before Potential 4Q Deceleration

We anticipate U.S. light vehicle (LV) SAAR of \(\sim 16.2 \mathrm{mn}\) in August - higher than the current Bloomberg consensus of \(\sim 16.4 \mathrm{mn}\) and representing only a slight deceleration from July's \(\sim 16.4 \mathrm{mn}\) rate - as a combination of strong consumer momentum amidst record U.S. equity prices, continued automaker absorption of (moderating) tariff costs, and a new pre- buy of EVs ahead of the accelerated expiration of U.S. federal tax credits on September 30 are expected to keep U.S. LV SAAR elevated in August (and likely September also) ahead of what we see as a potentially slower 4Q upon the cycling past (and payback for) 3Q's EV pre- buy and as automakers attempt to pass through more tariff costs via price increases associated with the rollout of 2026 model year vehicles around the October timeframe. The industry continues to observe strong demand trends, characterized by consumer momentum from July carrying into August, supported by a more plentiful assortment of inventory, the continued minimal pass- through of tariff costs by automakers on to consumers, and (likely temporary) increased interest in Battery Electric Vehicles (BEVs) as consumers seek to time purchases ahead of the expiration of federal EV tax credits worth up to \(\sim \$ 7,500\) under the Inflation Reduction Act. For more on the impact of stronger U.S. sales and more automaker absorption of tariff costs on the trend in industry production, see our August 19 note, "S&P Global Mobility Forecast Update: 2025 Global Light Vehicle Production Outlook Raised for Fourth Consecutive Month, Led by North America, Benefitting U.S.- based Supplier Guidance as Automakers Absorb Tariff Costs").

Industry participants we spoke to view the impressive August demand trends as roughly 'normalized,' with no pre- buy element ahead of anticipated pricing adjustments and tariff cost pass- throughs with the rollout of model year 2026 vehicles in the fall; however, we do see the current run- rate of sales as benefitting from pre- buy ahead of the expiration of EV tax credits and expect consumers to exhibit noticeable elasticity to expected price hikes over the next few months, suggesting November/December SAAR trends may better reflect the "new normal" demand environment than August/September. Our channel checks with automakers and franchise dealerships indicate that August's sales pace was bolstered into the third week of the month. While early month sales strength was predominantly driven by strong demand for small and mid- sized vehicles, larger pickup truck sales are expected to see a lift into the late- month Labor Day Weekend selling period. Significant BEV incentive activity (with BEV incentives estimated to track \(\sim \$ 6,700\) or \(+11.5\%\) higher than the blended industry average) has aided the sell- through of aged BEV inventory and is contributing to the current strong demand. As we have noted before, automakers have yet to substantially pass tariff costs on to consumers, but we see more potential for this upon the roll- out of 2026 model year variants, which allows price increases to be hidden to a greater degree given the reshuffling of various option packages, etc. We note that Audi recently announced price increases ranging from \(\sim +1.5\%\) to \(\sim +5.0\%\) for a number of its 2026 model year vehicles.

While there are transitory tailwinds stemming from BEV demand pull forward and potential interest rate cuts, we continue to see the industry eventually settling at a 'new normalized' SAAR level of \(- 15.5 \mathrm{~m}\) once near- term volatility subsides and anticipated tariff costs are fully passed along to consumers. Initially, post- pandemic, we estimated "new normal" SAAR at \(- 16 \mathrm{~m}\) , downwardly revised from \(- 17 \mathrm{~m}\) pre- COVID due to pandemic- era inflation. The introduction of \(25\%\) tariffs on imported vehicles announced in March 2025 led to a further downward adjustment to \(- 15.3 \mathrm{~m}\) inclusive of USMCA exemption, based on tariff costs estimated to equal \(- 8.2\%\) of retail vehicle prices ( \(- 1 / 2\) of which we expect to be passed on to the consumer) and a demand elasticity of \(- 1\) . Recent trade agreements, involving a lower tariff rate of \(- 10 - 15 \%\) vs. \(- 25 \%\) previously, have reduced our estimate of tariff costs to \(- 6.0 \%\) of retail vehicle prices ( \(- 1 / 2\) of which we expect to be passed on to the consumer), prompting our most recent adjustment of "new normal" SAAR to \(- 15.5 \mathrm{~m}\) (we use a weighted average tariff rate of \(17.5 \%\) , considering varying rates from different regions, and anticipate further reductions over time). Gravitation towards the 'new normalized' levels is still 2- 3 months out, in our view, and, as such, we expect full year 2025 U.S. light vehicle SAAR to close the year at \(- 16.0 \mathrm{~m}\) vs. YTD average of \(- 16.3 \mathrm{~m}\) through July- end. If U.S. tariffs on vehicles imported from Canada and Mexico eventually trend lower toward the \(10 \%\) to \(15 \%\) rate applied to imports from various countries reaching individual trade agreements with the U.S. - as was predicted by several CEOs and CFOs at our recent annual automotive conference, as outlined in our August 18 report, "2025 J.P. Morgan Automotive Conference Takeaways: Participants Across Auto Ecosystem Report Disparate Impacts from Tariffs (Dynamic Favors Suppliers \(>\) OEMs) EV Slowdown (We See DAN Biggest Beneficiary, Followed by GM, F, BWA)" - our view of "new normalized" demand could improve further, to the \(- 15.75 \mathrm{~m}\) range.

We forecast industry sales to rise by \(+4.4 \%\) y/y in August \((+8.2 \%\) y/y on a sell- day adjusted basis), with retail sales (JPM \(e + 4.4 \%\) y/y) expected to underperform fleet sales (JPM \(e + 10.1 \%\) y/y) due to easier prior- year comparisons for the fleet channel. Similar to in August 2024 (but atypical in comparison to the usual calendarization), much of the benefit of stronger sales from the Labor Day Weekend holiday selling period falls within the August reporting period rather than its historical inclusion in the September reporting period. The y/y trend for fleet sales is expected to improve sequentially into August, driven by easier prior- year comparisons and modest sales throughput improvement by automakers to fleet channels, especially rental car companies. We anticipate that industry incentives will increase by \(+1 \%\) m/m to \(\) 3,603\(in August, up from\) \ \(3,553\) in July, with the deviation from flat m/m expectations outlined by J.D. Power and our channel checks that are based on the first half of the month, largely driven by expectations of a late- month incentive enhancement in conjunction with the Labor Day weekend, and particularly geared towards pickup trucks, where the sales pace has lagged the broader industry in the first half of the month. Similarly, we anticipate average transaction prices (ATPs), which are calculated net of incentives, to decline by a lesser degree than J.D. Power estimates given our expectations of a tick up in the mix of higher- priced pickup trucks. We forecast a \(- \mathbb{S}250 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{m}\) (or \(- 0.6 \% \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{m}\) ) ATP decline in August compared to J.D. Power estimates calling for a \(- \mathbb{S}310\) or \(- 0.7 \% \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{m}\) ATP decline in August. Relative to the individual automakers we cover, we expect GM's August sales to rise \(+5 \%\) y/y (or to increase \(+9 \%\) on a sell- day adjusted basis) and Ford sales to rise \(+5 \%\) y/y (or to increase \(+10 \%\) on a sell- day adjusted basis). Note: There are 27 selling days in August 2025 versus 28 days in August 2024.

- Light Vehicle Selling Rate (Table 2): July US LV SAAR tracked \(-16.4 \mathrm{~m}\) (as per Wards Automotive), \(+3.7 \%\) y/y vs. \(-15.8 \mathrm{~m}\) in July 2024. Western Europe SAAR was \(11.4 \mathrm{~m}\) in July, tracking \(+3.3 \%\) y/y. China July SAAR, as per our estimate, rose \(+14.6 \%\) y/y. Elsewhere, we estimate SAAR in Japan was \(4.3 \mathrm{~m}\) in July (-3.6\% y/y) and Brazil \(2.6 \mathrm{~m}\) (+0.8\% y/y).
- US Market Share (Figure 8): Toyota (+142 bps) and GM (+49 bps) were the biggest market share gainers in July on a y/y basis, while Honda (-74 bps) and Nissan (-52 bps) lost the most share.
- US Dealer Inventories (Table 12): Industry days' supply stood at 47 days at the end of
July, down vs. 52 days a year ago and mostly softer comforted to the 10- year July average of 50 days. Days of supply sold at 57 for GM and 65 for Ford.
- US Incentives and Marketing Costs (Table 15): Industry-wide incentives rose \(+4.6\%\) y/y in July.

- Used Vehicle Pricing (Figure 30): US used car prices declined \(-0.4\%\) m/m \((+1.3\%\) y/y) in the first half of August after falling \(-0.5\%\) m/m \((+2.9\%\) y/y) in July, such that prices have declined \(-19.9\%\) from the all-time high reached in January 2022.

- Commodity Prices (Table 23): The cost of commodities used to manufacture an automobile fell \(-0.7\%\) m/m in August (to track \(+10.5\%\) y/y), driven by lower prices for Hot Rolled Steel \((-2.8\%\) m/m), Synthetic Rubber \((-1.0\%\) m/m), Cold Rolled Steel \((-0.7\%\) m/m) and Polypropylene \((-0.6\%\) m/m), partially offset by higher prices for Aluminium \((+2.3\%\) m/m), Copper \((+1.7\%\) m/m) and Lead \((+1.6\%\) m/m).
